# Prologue {#prologue}

AWS Controllers for Kubernetes (ACK) provides a bridge between Kubernetes and AWS services, enabling developers to manage AWS resources directly from within their Kubernetes clusters. This document explores the integration of ACK with Meshery, a multi-cloud management platform, to streamline the deployment and management of AWS resources in a Kubernetes environment. We will delve into the architecture, setup, and workflow involved in this integration, highlighting the benefits and potential use cases. By the end of this document, readers will have a comprehensive understanding of how to leverage ACK and Meshery to simplify their cloud-native application deployments on AWS. 

| Resources [ACK EC2 Tutorial](https://aws-controllers-k8s.github.io/community/docs/tutorials/ec2-example/)  [Sample Meshery Design with ACK](https://playground.meshery.io/extension/meshmap?mode=design&design=1fb02d08-99e8-4527-a7fc-cb974735fd81) [Demo video](https://youtu.be/NHx_UwL-PYg)  |

# An Example with AWS EC2 {#an-example-with-aws-ec2}

These instructions guide you through deploying an AWS EC2 controller using Meshery. This controller enables your Kubernetes cluster to communicate with the AWS API, allowing you to create, list, and delete EC2 instances directly from your cluster using kubectl commands.

## Overview of Steps Involved {#overview-of-steps-involved}

1. **Deploy the EC2 Controller with Meshery**  
   Using Meshery, you will first deploy the necessary Custom Resource Definitions (CRDs) and the EC2 controller to your Kubernetes cluster. This controller will manage AWS resources, particularly  EC2 instances, by communicating with the AWS API.  
     
2. **Provision AWS Resources**  
   After the EC2 controller is deployed, Meshery will facilitate the deployment of EC2 instances directly from the playground of your Kubernetes cluster. You can then manage these resources (create, list, delete) using Kubernetes commands.  
     
3. **Workflow**  
   The deployment of the EC2 controller and CRDs will be done through Meshery, ensuring that your cluster is equipped to communicate with AWS. Following the deployment of the controller, you can deploy and manage AWS EC2 instances directly from the Playground GUI. You can view your deployed AWS resources in Playground Operator Mode.

## Environment Setup {#environment-setup}

1. Set up an EKS cluster and  deploy Meshery In-cluster or set up a Minikube cluster and connect it to Meshery.  
   [https://docs.meshery.io/installation/kubernetes/eks](https://docs.meshery.io/installation/kubernetes/eks)  
2. Deploy the Custom resource definitions, Permissions, and controller pod using this Meshery design \- [https://playground.meshery.io/extension/meshmap?mode=design\&design=3dcbe4f0-542a-4edc-9b57-dcbcf76b9a25](https://playground.meshery.io/extension/meshmap?mode=design&design=3dcbe4f0-542a-4edc-9b57-dcbcf76b9a25)

## Actions in Meshery {#actions-in-meshery}

To get the ACK (AWS Controllers for Kubernetes) EC2 controller running in your cluster, you will need to deploy the necessary resources through a Helm chart. These resources include Custom Resource Definitions (CRDs), the required permissions, and the pod configuration. Together, they enable the EC2 controller to manage EC2 resources directly from your Kubernetes cluster.

1\. **Import the helm chart** using this [link](https://artifacthub.io/packages/olm/community-operators/ack-ec2-controller) and deploy.

2\. **Create a namespace component** called ack-system and add  all the components to the namespace.

3\. **Configure the Secret**:

1. Click on the **Secret** component in the design to open its configuration tab.  
2. Use an online Base64 converter to encode your AWS Access Key and Secret Access Key.  
3. In the Secret's configuration, under the data: section, input your encoded keys using the following variables:  
* AWS\_ACCESS\_KEY\_ID: *Base64-encoded access key*  
* AWS\_SECRET\_ACCESS\_KEY: *Base64-encoded secret key*

4\. **Configure the Controller Pod**:

1.  Next, configure the controller Pod to use the secret as environment variables  
2. In the Pod configuration, ensure the Pod mirrors the following YAML file, which references the secret for AWS credentials:

| apiVersion: v1kind: Podmetadata:  name: aws-credentials-podspec:  containers:  \- name: my-container    image: amazonlinux  \# Replace with your container image    env:    \- name: AWS\_ACCESS\_KEY\_ID      valueFrom:        secretKeyRef:          name: aws-credentials-secret   \# Name of the secret          key: AWS\_ACCESS\_KEY\_ID         \# Key in the secret to use    \- name: AWS\_SECRET\_ACCESS\_KEY      valueFrom:        secretKeyRef:          name: aws-credentials-secret   \# Name of the secret          key: AWS\_SECRET\_ACCESS\_KEY     \# Key in the secret to use |
| :---- |

## Deploy Resources {#deploy-resources}

To deploy your resources, go to actions, click deploy, select the right deployment environment.  
	  
**Create a VPC Workflow Design in Meshery to Deploy Custom Resources**

In this stage, you will design and deploy a VPC workflow using Meshery. This workflow will deploy the necessary AWS custom resources, including VPCs, subnets, NAT gateways, and other networking components required for the EC2 instance to operate within your AWS environment.

Import the resources using the YAML file [here](https://aws-controllers-k8s.github.io/community/docs/tutorials/ec2-example/)  
[https://playground.meshery.io/extension/meshmap?mode=design\&design=07624807-5701-4ea3-94f1-a65b8d793e9f](https://playground.meshery.io/extension/meshmap?mode=design&design=07624807-5701-4ea3-94f1-a65b8d793e9f)

![][image2]

At this point, you will import and deploy EC2 instances in your AWS environment through Meshery.

1\. Import and Deploy EC2 Instance components with YAML config [here](https://aws-controllers-k8s.github.io/community/docs/tutorials/ec2-example/) .  
2\. After deploying , you will see that your EC2 instances are deployed in your AWS environment as shown in the video demo.
